<p>Montana's solar irradiance levels are surprisingly strong despite its northern latitude, with most areas receiving 4.2-4.8 kWh/m¬≤/day of global horizontal irradiance. The state benefits from high altitude, low humidity, and minimal air pollution, which increase solar panel efficiency. Western Montana receives slightly less solar radiation due to mountain shading and increased cloud cover, while eastern Montana enjoys some of the best solar conditions in the northern United States. The combination of cold temperatures and intense sunlight is particularly beneficial for solar panel performance, as photovoltaic cells operate more efficiently in cooler conditions.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Montana are significant but manageable, with summer production potentially 2.5-3 times higher than winter output. A typical 6kW system in Billings might produce 1,000+ kWh in July but only 350-400 kWh in December. However, Montana's net metering policies allow homeowners to bank excess summer production as credits for winter use. Snow can temporarily reduce production, but panels typically shed snow quickly due to their smooth surface and heat generation, and the reflection of sunlight off snow can actually boost panel performance on clear winter days.</p>

<p>Expected annual production varies by location and system orientation, but most residential systems generate 1,200-1,400 kWh per installed kW annually. This means a 7kW system (typical for Montana homes) can produce 8,400-9,800 kWh per year, often covering 70-90% of average household electricity consumption. South-facing installations at 30-45 degree tilt angles optimize year-round production, though east-west orientations can provide more consistent daily output patterns that better match consumption.</p>

